</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C62FF89FF71FF33FE67F75D" blockId="4.[166,1225,175,362]" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">
at apical part of egg (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FE71FF33FDECF69D" box="[422,514,175,202]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[172,205,1736,1758]" captionTargetBox="[174,1228,201,1672]" captionTargetId="figure-5@1.[174,1228,201,1672]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–6. Eggs of Acronictinae: Acronicta megacephala. Scale bars: 1, 4 — 100 µm; 2, 3, 5, 6 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453276" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453276/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 4–5</figureCitation>
) and rest surface as case bound pigtails (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FC27FF33FBDFF69D" box="[1008,1073,175,202]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[172,205,1736,1758]" captionTargetBox="[174,1228,201,1672]" captionTargetId="figure-5@1.[174,1228,201,1672]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1–6. Eggs of Acronictinae: Acronicta megacephala. Scale bars: 1, 4 — 100 µm; 2, 3, 5, 6 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453276" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453276/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Transverse walls not looked over. Aeropyles clearly expressed. The entire surface of a small, densely placed fiber (
<figureCitation id="ACA42A056C62FF89FEE9FF73FE92F75D" box="[318,380,239,266]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[166,199,1708,1730]" captionTargetBox="[166,1224,181,1677]" captionTargetId="figure-8@2.[166,1224,181,1680]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 7–12. Eggs of Acronictinae: 7 — Acronicta megacephala; 8–11 — Acronicta rumicis; 12 — Craniophora ligustri. Scale bars: 8, 10, 12 — 100 µm; 7, 9, 11 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453282" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453282/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">fig. 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="342036806C62FF89FF0CFE93FCDCF71D" blockId="4.[166,1225,175,362]" pageId="4" pageNumber="357">
Shape of gnawed holes in eggs. Larva nibbling out round opening at apical area of the egg; only central cover on thin “stem” remained (
